In TypeScript, you can use type assertions to specify that a value is of a certain type, even if the type is not known in advance. This is useful when you have an incomplete type definition or when you want to provide a fallback type in case the type is not explicitly defined.

Here's an example of how to use type assertions in TypeScript:

```typescript
function sum(a: number | string): number {
    return a + 1;
}

const result = sum(3.5);
// result will be of type number

const result = sum("Hello");
// result will be of type string
```

In this example, `sum` is a function that takes either a number or a string. The type assertion `| number | string` specifies that the function can handle values of either type. In the first case, the type assertion is satisfied, so `result` will have a type of `number`. In the second case, the type assertion is not satisfied, so `result` will have a type of `string`.

You can also specify a type that is not known at compile-time by using a `*` wildcard:

```typescript
function sum(a: number | string): number {
    return a + 1;
}

const result = sum(3.5);
// result will be of type number

const result = sum("Hello");
// result will be of type string
```

Using type assertions can help you write more robust and type-safe code, even when you don't have the full type definition for a value at compile-time.

